<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
    <title>RASH case sheet part</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="Case_sheet_styles.css">
    <script src="https://www.youtube.com/iframe_api"></script>
</head>
<body>

    <div class="derma infectious General">
        <h3>1ST COMPLAINT: RASH</h3>
        
            <!-- S: Site -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>S</strong>: Site & Distribution</span>
                <span class="verbal">"Where did the rash start, and where has it spread?"</span>
                <ul>
                    <li>LOCALIZED
                        <ul><li class="infectious">Fungal (Tinea)</li><li class="derma">Contact Dermatitis</li></ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>GENERALIZED (Widespread)
                        <ul>
                            <li class="infectious">Viral Exanthem (See specific patterns below)</li>
                            <li class="rheumatic">Drug Eruption</li>
                            <li class="derma">Eczema Flare</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>SPECIFIC DISTRIBUTION PATTERNS
                        <ul>
                            <li class="derma">Flexures (bends of elbows/knees): 
                                <ul><li>Atopic Dermatitis (Eczema)</li></ul></li>
                            <li class="derma">Extensors (outside of elbows/knees): 
                                <ul><li>Psoriasis</li></ul></li>
                            <li class="cns">Dermatomal (one nerve strip): 
                                <ul><li>Shingles (Herpes Zoster)</li></ul></li>
                            <li class="infectious">Face first, then down body (Cephalocaudal): 
                                <ul><li>Measles, Rubella</li></ul></li>
                            <li class="infectious">Trunk first, then out: 
                                <ul><li>Roseola, Varicella</li></ul></li>
                            <li class="infectious">"Slapped Cheeks": 
                                <ul><li>Fifth Disease</li></ul></li>
                            <li class="infectious">Hands, Feet, and Mouth: HFMD</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>

            <!-- O: Onset -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>O</strong>: Onset</span>
                <span class="verbal">"When did it appear? Suddenly over minutes, or gradually over days?"</span>
                 <ul>
                    <li>ACUTE (Minutes-Hours): 
                        <ul><li class="rheumatic emergency">Urticaria</li><li class="derma">Contact Dermatitis</li></ul></li>
                    <li>SUBACUTE (Days): 
                        <ul><li class="infectious">Viral Exanthems</li><li class="rheumatic">Drug Reactions</li></ul></li>
                    <li>CHRONIC (Weeks-Months): 
                        <ul><li class="derma rheumatic">Eczema, Psoriasis</li></ul></li>
                </ul>
            </li>

            <!-- D: Duration -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>D</strong>: Duration</span>
                <span class="verbal">"How long do individual spots last? Do they come and go, or stay put?"</span>
            </li>

            <!-- A/R: Aggravating / Relieving Factors -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>A/R</strong>: Aggravating & Relieving Factors</span>
                <span class="verbal">"Does anything make it better or worse?"</span>
            </li>

            <!-- C: Character -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>C</strong>: Character (Morphology)</span>
                <span class="verbal">"What do the spots look like? Flat, bumpy, blisters? Are they itchy?"</span>
                <ul>
                    <li>MORPHOLOGY
                        <ul>
                            <li>Maculopapular (red bumps/spots): 
                                <ul><li class="infectious">Measles, Rubella, Roseola</li></ul></li>
                            <li>Vesicular (blisters): 
                                <ul><li class="infectious">Varicella, HFMD, Shingles</li></ul></li>
                            <li>Pustular (pus-filled): 
                                <ul><li class="infectious derma">Folliculitis, Acne</li></ul></li>
                            <li>Wheals (hives): 
                                <ul><li class="rheumatic">Urticaria</li></ul></li>
                            <li>Lacy/Reticular: 
                                <ul><li class="infectious">Fifth Disease</li></ul></li>
                            <li>Sandpaper-like: 
                                <ul><li class="infectious git">Scarlet Fever</li></ul></li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>

            <!-- R: Radiation (Spread Pattern) -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>R</strong>: Radiation (Spread)</span>
                <span class="verbal">"We've covered the spread, thank you."</span>
            </li>
            
            <!-- A: Associated Symptoms (with VIRAL EXANTHEM SUB-MODULE) -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>A</strong>: Associated Symptoms</span>
                <span class="verbal">"Any other symptoms like fever, cough, joint pain, or mouth sores?"</span>
                <ul>
                    <li>GENERAL
                        <ul><li class="rheumatic">Joint Pain (HSP, Viral Arthritis)</li><li class="derma">New foods, medications, soaps?</li></ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>DEHYDRATION SIGNS</strong> – dry nappies, lethargy, sunken eyes.</li>
                    <li><strong>MEDICATION HISTORY (child)</strong> – paracetamol? <span class="warning">Ibuprofen</span>? steroids? any recent antibiotics.</li>
                    <li><strong>FEVER PROFILE</strong> – 
                        <ul>
                            <li>peak temperature, timing in relation to rash, response to paracetamol; note that high fever <strong>preceding</strong> rash that then falls ( ↘︎ ) suggests <span class="infectious">Roseola</span>.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>

                    <li class="infectious">CLUES FOR VIRAL EXANTHEMS
                        <ul>
                            <li><b>Fever Timing:</b>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>High fever first, THEN rash appears as fever breaks? -> <b class="infectious">Roseola</b></li>
                                    <li>Fever and rash at the same time? -> <b class="infectious">Measles, Rubella, Varicella</b></li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                            <li><b>Prodrome (Symptoms BEFORE rash):</b>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Cough, Coryza (runny nose), Conjunctivitis (3 C's)? -> <b class="infectious">Measles</b></li>
                                    <li>Sore throat? -> <b class="infectious git">Scarlet Fever</b></li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                            <li><b>Mouth / Mucosal Signs:</b>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Koplik spots (white spots in cheeks)? -> <b class="infectious">Measles</b></li>
                                    <li>Mouth ulcers? -> <b class="infectious">HFMD / Herpangina</b></li>
                                    <li>Strawberry tongue? -> <b class="infectious git">Scarlet Fever / Kawasaki</b></li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                             <li><b>Other Key Signs:</b>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Swollen nodes behind ears? -> <b class="infectious">Rubella</b></li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>PRURITUS (ITCH): <span class="infectious derma">Scabies, Eczema, Varicella</span> are intensely itchy.</li>

<li><strong>ITCH SEVERITY & SKIN CARE</strong> – quantify pruritus; ask about scratching, calamine, antihistamine, short nails, emollient baths.</li>

<li>PAIN: <span class="cns">Shingles</span> is classically painful.</li>

                </ul>
            </li>
            
            <!-- M: Medical / Medication Background -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>M</strong>: Medical / Medication Background</span>
                <span class="verbal">"Does your child have any other health problems or regular medicines? Any allergies?"</span>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Past Medical History</strong> – eczema, asthma, immunosuppression, prematurity.</li>
                    <li><strong>Drug Allergies</strong> – especially antibiotics.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>

            <!-- P: Progression -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>P</strong>: Progression</span>
                <span class="verbal">"How have the spots changed over time since they first appeared?"</span>
                 <ul><li>Multiple stages at once (spots, blisters, crusts)? → <span class="infectious">Varicella</span></li></ul>
            </li>

            <!-- P: Pattern & People -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>P</strong>: Pattern & People</span>
                <span class="verbal">"Is anyone else sick? Any recent travel? Are immunisations up to date?"</span>
                 <ul>
                    <li class="infectious">SICK CONTACTS (school, nursery, home)</li>
                    <li class="General">IMMUNISATION STATUS (MMR, <strong>Varicella</strong>)</li>
                    <li><strong>HIGH‑RISK CONTACTS</strong> – pregnant household members, newborns, immunocompromised relatives (require separate advice).</li>
                </ul>
            </li>

            <!-- E: Effect on life -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>E</strong>: Effect on Life</span>
                <span class="verbal">"How is your child's overall energy? Are they playful, or very sick?"</span>
                <ul>
                    <li>Appears generally well -> <b class="infectious">Roseola, Fifth Disease</b></li>
                    <li>Appears miserable/very unwell -> <b class="infectious">Measles</b></li>
                </ul>
            </li>

            <!-- R: Red Flags -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>R</strong>: Red Flags</span>
                <span class="verbal">"I must ask some specific questions. Does the rash not fade with pressure? Any trouble breathing?"</span>
                <ul>
                    <li class="emergency infectious">NON-BLANCHING RASH (Petechiae/Purpura) + FEVER -> <b class="emergency">Meningococcemia</b></li>
                    <li class="emergency rheumatic">HIVES + Swelling/Difficulty Breathing -> <b class="emergency">Anaphylaxis</b></li>
                    <li class="emergency derma">BLISTERING/PEELING with mucosal involvement -> <b class="emergency">SJS/TEN</b></li>
                    <li class="infectious cvs rheumatic emergency">FEVER > 5 days + Redness (eyes, mouth) + Swelling (hands/feet) -> <b class="emergency">Kawasaki Disease</b></li>
                    <li class="warning">Rash becoming <strong>red, hot or painful</strong> (secondary bacterial infection).</li>
                    <li class="warning">Ataxia / unsteady gait (possible varicella cerebellitis).</li>
                </ul>
            </li>

            <!-- S: Severity -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>S</strong>: Severity / Scale</span>
                <span class="verbal">"On a scale of 1 to 10, how itchy or bothersome is the rash?"</span>
            </li>

            <!-- Parent / Carer Risk Discussion -->
            <li class="point">
                <span class="description"><strong>Parent / Carer Exposure</strong></span>
                <span class="verbal">"Have you ever had chicken pox or been vaccinated? Are you or anyone at home pregnant, on cancer treatment, or taking medicines that weaken immunity?"</span>
                <ul>
                    <li>If <em>non‑immune</em> and exposure within 24 h → discuss adult vaccination or prophylactic aciclovir.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            
    </div>
    
    <script src="theme-toggle.js"></script>
    <script src="Iframe_height_mothership.js"></script>
    <script src="Iframe_height.js"></script>
</body>
</html>